An Arduino Uno serves as the circuit's controller, reading two push buttons and managing a 7-segment display to indicate numbers from 0 to 9.
The 7-segment display comprises seven LEDs configured to represent the numeral "8," with specific segments activated to display any digit, 
connected to Arduino pins 2-8, and linked to a common ground through a 330Ω resistor to prevent LED damage.
The buttons facilitate counting operations; the right button, attached to pin 10, increments the count, while the left button, connected to pin 9, decrements it, 
each with a 10kΩ pull-down resistor to mitigate noise interference.
The code initializes the counter at zero, incrementing it when the right button is pressed (if below 9) and decrementing it with the left button (if above 0), 
subsequently updating the display pins to reflect the current digit.
Button bounce, causing erratic counting, is mitigated by implementing a 200 millisecond pause after each press; if the display remains inactive, 
it indicates improper grounding, while random counter fluctuations suggest issues with pull-down resistors.
